sec.p:
Together, nematodes of the genus Fergusobia Currie 1937 (
Christie 1941 )
( Tylenchida : Neotylenchidae ) and flies of the genus Fergusonina Malloch 1924 ( Diptera : Fergusoninidae ) form galls on some Myrtaceae (
Currie 1937 ; Giblin-Davis et al . 2004 b;
Taylor et al . 2005 ; Nelson et al.2014 ). Each species of Fergusonina is associated with a particular species of Fergusobia , in mutualisms that are generally plant host species specific and each induce one gall form (Giblin-Davis et al . 2004 ;
Taylor et al . 2005 ;
Ye et al . 2007 ;
Davies et al . 2010 a
; Nelson et al.2014 ; S. Scheffer unpub. data).

Given the specificity of the Fergusobia / Fergusonina mutualism, the morphology of the dorsal shield, a cuticular structure on the dorsum of third stage fly larvae and pupae, can be used as a guide in identifying the phylogenetic group to which an associated nematode belongs (
Davies et al . 2010 a
).

Morphological and sequencing studies have provided evidence for about 20 clades of Fergusobia nematodes (
Ye et al . 2007 ,
Davies et al . 2010 a
). This paper is the tenth of a series describing or re-describing species of Fergusobia , from particular gall forms and/or host plant species, from respective clades of nematodes. Various Fergusobia / Fergusonina galls have been found with Melaleuca Linnaeus 1767 , nom. cons. species (
Giblin-Davis et al . 2001 ;
Taylor et al . 2005 ). Of these, the most commonly collected are flower and shoot bud galls from broadleaved Melaleuca spp., probably because they are the largest and most obvious forms.

Molecular analyses of nematodes collected from narrow-leaved Melaleuca spp. from several locations in Queensland and New South Wales suggested that they occurred in two clades (
Davies et al . 2010 a
), i . e ., that at least two lineages of nematodes induce similar gall forms on a range of Melaleuca species. The possible phylogenetic relationships of these nematode/fly associations from galls on narrow-leaved Melaleuca spp. are discussed.

Nematode material. Nematodes were collected from galls as described in Davies and Giblin-Davis ( 2004 ), and relaxed and fixed in hot 3 % formalin. Latitude and longitude were determined using a Magellan® GPS 315 / 320 . Measurements are given in µm (
Davies et al . 2010 b
). To find the relative diameter of the cephalic region, the diameter of the nematode body was measured about 3 annules posterior to the cephalic region, and the diameter of the latter was determined as a percentage of the anterior body diameter. Similarly, to determine the proportion of the body diameter occupied by the oesophageal glands, diameter of both body and glands were measured at the point where the glands were widest. In the descriptions of the infective females, the term ‘uterus’ means the part of the reproductive tract extending from the vulva to the distal end of the oviduct.

