sec.p:
Body shape of the parthenogenetic females is a useful character for diagnosis of this group. Parthenogenetic females of Fergusobia spp. from broad-leaved melaleucas and from Syzygium luehmannii (F. Muell.) L.A.S. Johnson 1962 in Australia tend to be more ventrally curved, i.e. more C-shaped (Davies & Giblin-Davis 2004 ;
Davies et al.2014 d
) than those collected from narrow-leaved melaleucas.

None of the Fergusobia described from broad-leaved melaleucas has an extensile uterus (Davies & Giblin- Davis 2004 ;
Davies et al.2010 a
). However, this has been observed in several undescribed species of Fergusobia from Angophora Cavanilles 1797 (
Davies et al.2014 a
) and Corymbia Hill & Johnson 1995 (including F. magna (
Siddiqi 1986 ;
Davies et al.2010 b
) and F. rileyii (
Davies et al.2012 a
)) and Syzygium R. Brown ex Gaertner 1828 ( F. tolgaensis (
Davies et al.2014 d
)). It was apparently illustrated by Siddiqi (1986 , 1994 respectively) for F. jambophila and F. brevicauda , from S. cumini (L.) Skeels 1912 and E. deglupta Bl. 1849 respectively from tropical India and The Philippines . It has only been observed once from galls on subgenus Symphyomyrtus , in F. camaldulensae (Davies et al.2011 a) from E. camaldulensis , in southern Australia . This suggests that parthenogenetic females with extensile uteri occur more commonly in northern Australia and tropical areas, where it is thought that Melaleuca evolved and diverged (
Barlow 1988 ), and that this may be a ‘primitive’ character for the nematode. It is possible that this character is associated with some variation in the life history of the nematode, e.g ., they may be ovoviviparous.

As discussed in
Davies et al . ( 2014 d)
, the size of the angle at which the spicule is bent appears to vary in Fergusobia species from some broad-leaved and most narrow-leaved Melaleuca spp. known to be hosts and from Syzygium . The angle of the bend near the centre of the spicule is at least 90 º in all spicules illustrated here (
). It is difficult to determine when a spicule is arcuate, and when it is angular, possibly reflecting the position of the spicule when viewed (
Siddiqi 1986 ; K.A. Davies personal observation
).

In general, the Fergusobia spp. collected from unilocular and basal shoot galls on narrow-leaved melaleucas are smaller than Fergusobia spp. from TLBG and FBG. They are closer in size to species collected from FLG’s and small or unilocular bud galls (
Davies et al . 2010 a
). This may reflect the amount of resources available to individual nematodes, rather than genetic differences. The arcuate shape of the parthenogenetic females of the former clearly separates them from the tight C-shapes of the Fergusobia spp. from TLBG and FBG (
Davies et al . 2010 a
).

